    "decisionConsequence": "High",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to predict absolute hemolysis levels across operating conditions for a centrifugal blood pump used as a ventricular assist device (VAD). Model influence is HIGH (model is primary basis for hemolysis acceptance); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect prediction could result in chronic patient hemolysis requiring clinical intervention). Model Risk Level 5 — the highest in the Morrison assessment.",
    "deviceClass": "Class III",
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou2-vad",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to predict absolute hemolysis index values for a Class III VAD device across 5 flow-speed combinations. Results must demonstrate hemolysis below absolute clinical threshold (not relative to predicate). Requires Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification on hemolysis predictions.",
    "modelInfluence": "High",
    "name": "COU2: Ventricular assist device use (Class III)",
    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/morrison-cou2-primary-hemolysis-index",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Primary hemolysis index comparison — CFD vs. bench (5 operating points)",
      "comparedAgainst": "https://uofa.net/synth/data/fda-pump-bench-hemolysis-dataset",
      "description": "The CFD-predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) was compared against in-vitro measurements conducted on the FDA generic centrifugal pump at five flow-speed operating points (2 L/min at 2500 RPM, 3 L/min at 2500 RPM, 4 L/min at 2500 RPM, 3 L/min at 3500 RPM, and 5 L/min at 3500 RPM). The bench testing was performed in a recirculating loop using bovine blood with haematocrit 33 ± 2%, temperature controlled at 37 °C, and run duration of 6 hours per point. NIH was calculated using the ASTM F1841 formula. CFD predictions used the Giersiepen power-law hemolysis model integrated along Lagrangian particle trajectories (n = 50 000 particles per operating point). Monte Carlo sampling (n = 1000 draws) was applied to the three Giersiepen model coefficients using literature-derived uncertainty bounds. The mean predicted NIH agreed with measured NIH within 18% across all five operating points; at the worst-case point (5 L/min, 3500 RPM) the 95th-percentile Monte Carlo bound remained below the clinical threshold of 0.1 g/100 L. The comparison was judged to partially satisfy the output comparison credibility factor at Gradation 2, with the gap to Gradation 3 attributed to the single-model-form hemolysis law and absence of mesh-resolved boundary-layer shear stress validation. All raw comparison data, particle tracking logs, and Monte Carlo sample archives are retained in the project data repository under accession FDA-PUMP-COU2-2026."
    },
    {
